        "number": 4,
        "title": "Gabriel's answer — seventy weeks of redemption",
        "range": "9:20-27",
        "excerpt": "Seventy weeks have been decreed for your people and your holy city, to finish the transgression, to make an end of sin, to make atonement for iniquity, to bring in everlasting righteousness, to seal up vision and prophecy, and to anoint the most holy place.",
        "body": "While Daniel is still praying, Gabriel arrives (9:20-21). The chronological note is precise — *about the time of the evening offering*, roughly 3 PM, the hour of the daily *minchah* in the temple in Jerusalem. The temple has been destroyed for nearly half a century, but Daniel still prays by temple time. The displaced saint keeps the rhythm of the worship that was, anticipating the worship that will be.\n\nGabriel says two things that change everything. *At the beginning of your supplications the command was issued* (9:23) — the answer was launched before the prayer was finished. The praying believer is not generating God's response; he is receiving an answer already dispatched. And *you are highly esteemed* (*chamudot*, *one greatly loved*) — Daniel's identity is settled in heaven before the oracle is delivered.\n\nThen 9:24-27 — four verses that have generated more interpretation than perhaps any other in the OT. The structure:\n\n**The total span (9:24).** *Seventy weeks are decreed* — literally *cut out* (*chatakh*, a hapax in this sense) for Israel and Jerusalem. Seventy *shavuim* — sevens — almost certainly seven *years* each, given the chapter's context (the seventy *years* of v. 2, the sabbath-of-years calendar of Leviticus 25). Total: 490 years. Within this span, six redemptive goals are accomplished: three deal with sin (*finish transgression, end sin, atone for iniquity*), three establish holiness (*bring in everlasting righteousness, seal vision and prophecy, anoint the most holy*). The atonement-language (*kipher*) is priestly; the *anointing of the most holy* (*qodesh qodashim*) evokes the tabernacle consecration of Exodus 30:26-29 and Leviticus 8.\n\n**The first 69 weeks (9:25).** *From the issuing of a decree to restore and rebuild Jerusalem until Messiah the Prince there will be seven weeks and sixty-two weeks* — 49 + 434 = 483 years. The decree in view is most likely Artaxerxes' authorization to Nehemiah in 445 BC (Nehemiah 2:1-8), which specifically authorized the rebuilding of the city and its walls. Sir Robert Anderson's calculation (using 360-day prophetic years) lands at AD 32-33, the year of Christ's triumphal entry. Even with more conservative calculations, the 483-year span lands in the early first century AD — the documented life of Jesus of Nazareth.\n\n**The hinge (9:26).** *After the sixty-two weeks the Messiah will be cut off and have nothing.* The verb *karat* (cut off) is the standard OT term for violent death, often covenant-curse death (Genesis 17:14; Leviticus 17:4). *Mashiach yikkaret* — *Messiah will be cut off* — predicted, centuries before the cross, that the Anointed One would die without receiving the kingdom in that moment. *And have nothing* (*ve-ein lo*) — at His death, no visible inheritance, no kingdom, no people. Isaiah 53:8 had said the same thing in different words. Then *the people of the prince who is to come will destroy the city and the sanctuary* — the Roman legions under Titus, AD 70.\n\n**The seventieth week (9:27).** *He will make a firm covenant with the many for one week, but in the middle of the week he will put a stop to sacrifice and grain offering; and on the wing of abominations will come one who makes desolate.* Here orthodox interpreters divide.\n\n**The premillennial / dispensational reading**: The *he* of v. 27 is the *prince who is to come* (v. 26b) — a future Antichrist figure who imposes a seven-year covenant on Israel, breaks it at the midpoint by stopping the rebuilt-temple sacrifices, sets up the abomination of desolation (cf. Matthew 24:15; 2 Thessalonians 2:3-4), and meets his decreed end at Christ's return. A gap exists between week 69 and week 70 — the church age — during which the prophetic clock for Israel pauses.\n\n**The amillennial / classical Reformed reading** (Young, Calvin in part): The *he* of v. 27 is Messiah Himself. The *firm covenant with the many* is the new covenant inaugurated by His blood (Matthew 26:28). The *cessation of sacrifice* in the middle of the week is His death, which renders the temple cultus obsolete (Hebrews 10:11-14). The abomination and destruction refer to AD 70. The seventy weeks reach completion in the apostolic age.\n\nBoth readings affirm the same essential truths: (a) Messiah's coming and death were calendared in advance; (b) the city and sanctuary were destroyed after the Messiah was cut off; (c) God's redemptive purpose runs on a fixed schedule, *decreed* (*charats*, 9:26-27) and *cut out* (*chatakh*, 9:24). Whatever the precise mapping of the seventieth week, the chapter's theological force is clear: history is not random, the Messiah is not generic, and the timetable is God's.\n\nThe whole chapter ends here. Daniel asked about seventy years; God answered with seventy weeks. The petitioner asked about returning to a city; the Giver answered with a Messiah who would atone for sin and bring in everlasting righteousness. This is the canonical pattern of prayer — God answers more deeply than the question, more broadly than the request, and more permanently than the timeline we imagined.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shavuim shivim nechtak* (9:24) — *seventy sevens are cut out*. The verb *chatakh* appears nowhere else in the OT; the choice of a unique verb to introduce a unique decree is itself a literary signal. *Mashiach nagid* (9:25) — *Messiah the Prince*, the construct chain making *Anointed One* a title not merely an adjective. *Yikkaret mashiach ve-ein lo* (9:26) — *Messiah will be cut off and have nothing* — the most explicit pre-NT prediction of the suffering Messiah outside Isaiah 53."
